The South African Municipal Workers’ Union says it won't be taking part in the 'salary cut challenge'. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The South African Municipal Workers Union (Samwu) says it won't be taking part in the 'salary cut challenge'. This was in response to a suggestion that the Ekurhuleni municipality take a five percent salary cut for three months. READ: Motsepe Foundation pledges R1bn to help fight COVID-19 Samwu's Koena Ramatlou says workers can't afford to earn less. "Workers are not going to be participating in any tournament that is meant to deal with salaries," said Ramatlou. WATCH: Ramaphosa, Cabinet to take pay cuts "There is no discussion in Ekurhuleni that involves members of Samwu or municipal workers about any form of cut of salaries." Ramatlou said employees are welcome to make a donation on their own. READ: EFF MPs, MPLs to contribute portion of salaries to Solidarity Fund "It’s a personal decision. We don’t want to stop employees from doing their own gestures," he said. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.